WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.140 --> 00:00:00.630
Alright.

2
00:00:00.630 --> 00:00:03.025
Today we're gonna level up your accessibility testing.

3
00:00:03.275 --> 00:00:04.625
We're moving past the basics

4
00:00:04.625 --> 00:00:07.265
and diving into some advanced screen reader patterns.

5
00:00:07.645 --> 00:00:09.145
The whole point here is to focus on

6
00:00:09.145 --> 00:00:11.785
what you should actually hear when you're testing the really

7
00:00:11.785 --> 00:00:13.065
complex parts of your designs.

8
00:00:13.355 --> 00:00:15.045
Let's get into it. Look,

9
00:00:15.225 --> 00:00:17.485
you probably already have the fundamentals down, right?

10
00:00:17.895 --> 00:00:20.125
Navigating headings, clicking on links,

11
00:00:20.155 --> 00:00:21.565
that stuff is super important,

12
00:00:22.025 --> 00:00:25.005
but it's not where the most frustrating accessibility bugs

13
00:00:25.005 --> 00:00:27.525
tend to hide the real problems, the ones

14
00:00:27.525 --> 00:00:30.485
that truly block users, they live inside Those complex,

15
00:00:30.595 --> 00:00:33.245
interactive components we design and build every day.

16
00:00:33.865 --> 00:00:35.085
So here's what we're gonna cover.

17
00:00:35.495 --> 00:00:38.645
We'll walk through five key patterns, data tables,

18
00:00:38.665 --> 00:00:40.845
tricky forms, modal dialogues,

19
00:00:40.945 --> 00:00:43.885
and dynamic content like tabs and live updates.

20
00:00:44.275 --> 00:00:45.565
Then we will wrap it all up

21
00:00:45.565 --> 00:00:48.325
with a really simple three question test you can use on

22
00:00:48.325 --> 00:00:49.605
basically any component.

23
00:00:50.015 --> 00:00:52.405
Think of this as your personal audio guide

24
00:00:52.425 --> 00:00:54.045
for spotting bugs in the wild.

25
00:00:54.735 --> 00:00:57.925
First up, data tables, I mean, they're everywhere, right?

26
00:00:58.295 --> 00:01:00.685
Dashboards, pricing pages, you name it.

27
00:01:01.105 --> 00:01:04.085
For a screen reader, user, a table isn't just a visual grid,

28
00:01:04.315 --> 00:01:06.205
it's a whole special mode of navigation,

29
00:01:06.545 --> 00:01:07.725
and if it isn't built right,

30
00:01:07.865 --> 00:01:09.965
it just becomes a meaningless jumble of data.

31
00:01:10.795 --> 00:01:11.975
So I want you to picture this.

32
00:01:12.075 --> 00:01:14.255
You're navigating a page with a screen reader

33
00:01:14.315 --> 00:01:16.655
and you land smack in the middle of a data table.

34
00:01:17.115 --> 00:01:19.015
What's the very first thing you need to hear

35
00:01:19.075 --> 00:01:20.895
to even understand what's going on?

36
00:01:21.815 --> 00:01:23.635
The right experience is all about context.

37
00:01:24.125 --> 00:01:26.075
First, the screen reader should announce the

38
00:01:26.075 --> 00:01:27.275
table and its dimensions.

39
00:01:27.275 --> 00:01:31.075
Something like table with five rows, four columns, awesome.

40
00:01:31.545 --> 00:01:32.995
Then as you move into a cell,

41
00:01:33.085 --> 00:01:35.475
it'll pair the column header with the data itself.

42
00:01:36.005 --> 00:01:37.635
Price 29.99.

43
00:01:37.895 --> 00:01:41.595
But if all you hear is 29.99, well that's a huge failure.

44
00:01:42.195 --> 00:01:44.475
A number without any context is just noise.

45
00:01:45.645 --> 00:01:48.135
Okay, let's move on to our next pattern.

46
00:01:48.565 --> 00:01:51.895
Complex forms, and just like with tables,

47
00:01:52.005 --> 00:01:53.815
context is everything.

48
00:01:54.605 --> 00:01:57.095
This is especially true in those long checkout flows

49
00:01:57.095 --> 00:01:58.735
where you might have the same field label,

50
00:01:58.805 --> 00:02:01.615
like street address show up in a couple of different places.

51
00:02:02.615 --> 00:02:04.395
So here's the million dollar question.

52
00:02:05.015 --> 00:02:07.755
If a user lands on a field that says street address,

53
00:02:08.135 --> 00:02:09.475
how in the world do they know if it's

54
00:02:09.475 --> 00:02:11.835
for their shipping address or their billing address?

55
00:02:12.375 --> 00:02:15.235
The answer has everything to do with proper grouping

56
00:02:15.895 --> 00:02:16.915
in a well-built form.

57
00:02:17.055 --> 00:02:19.035
The screen reader gives you this beautiful,

58
00:02:19.065 --> 00:02:20.635
logical flow of information.

59
00:02:20.935 --> 00:02:23.635
It announces the group first shipping address.

60
00:02:23.945 --> 00:02:26.475
Then it gives you the field details, street address, edit,

61
00:02:26.545 --> 00:02:30.355
text required the failure, it's just confusing.

62
00:02:30.355 --> 00:02:33.955
Silence. All you hear is edit text with absolutely no clue

63
00:02:33.955 --> 00:02:36.035
what it's for or if you even have to fill it out.

64
00:02:36.805 --> 00:02:40.135
Alright? Pattern number three, the modal dialogue.

65
00:02:40.515 --> 00:02:42.295
Now you're gonna wanna lean in for this one

66
00:02:42.295 --> 00:02:44.575
because if there is one single component

67
00:02:44.575 --> 00:02:46.455
that consistently gives teams trouble

68
00:02:46.555 --> 00:02:49.335
and just breaks accessibility, it's this one.

69
00:02:49.685 --> 00:02:52.055
Getting modals right is not a nice to have.

70
00:02:52.405 --> 00:02:55.825
It's a must have. And hey, that's not just my opinion.

71
00:02:56.215 --> 00:02:58.545
It's a well known fact in the accessibility world

72
00:02:58.775 --> 00:03:02.205
that managing keyboard focus when a dialogue opens is just

73
00:03:02.255 --> 00:03:03.805
incredibly hard to get right.

74
00:03:04.185 --> 00:03:06.165
But here's the good news. As a designer,

75
00:03:06.545 --> 00:03:07.925
you can catch these failures.

76
00:03:08.225 --> 00:03:10.725
You just have to know what to listen for and what to try.

77
00:03:11.625 --> 00:03:13.245
So here is your four step test

78
00:03:13.345 --> 00:03:14.765
for any modal you come across.

79
00:03:15.465 --> 00:03:16.725
One, when it opens,

80
00:03:16.795 --> 00:03:19.325
does the screen reader clearly announce the dialogues?

81
00:03:19.325 --> 00:03:22.005
Title two, when you press the tab key,

82
00:03:22.035 --> 00:03:23.845
does your focus stay trapped inside

83
00:03:23.865 --> 00:03:24.965
or can you get to the page

84
00:03:24.965 --> 00:03:26.325
behind it because that's a failure.

85
00:03:27.055 --> 00:03:30.285
Three. Does the escape key close it? It definitely should.

86
00:03:30.705 --> 00:03:32.165
And four, this is the big one.

87
00:03:32.295 --> 00:03:34.365
After it closes, does your focus go right

88
00:03:34.365 --> 00:03:35.445
back to the button that opened it?

89
00:03:35.865 --> 00:03:38.645
If you get a no on any of these, you found a bug.

90
00:03:39.645 --> 00:03:41.775
Okay, next up is dynamic content.

91
00:03:42.105 --> 00:03:43.855
We're talking about parts of your interface

92
00:03:43.855 --> 00:03:46.375
that change without the whole page reloading.

93
00:03:46.815 --> 00:03:48.415
A perfect example is a tab panel.

94
00:03:48.635 --> 00:03:50.655
You know, you click a tab, the content changes,

95
00:03:50.995 --> 00:03:53.455
but the URL at the top of the browser stays the same.

96
00:03:54.125 --> 00:03:56.455
When you land on a proper set of tabs,

97
00:03:56.595 --> 00:03:59.175
you should hear everything you need to know its role,

98
00:03:59.595 --> 00:04:02.535
its name, its state, and its position in the set.

99
00:04:02.685 --> 00:04:06.975
Something like tab profile selected to a four.

100
00:04:07.485 --> 00:04:09.055
This tells you exactly what it is,

101
00:04:09.105 --> 00:04:11.215
which one is active and how many there are.

102
00:04:11.635 --> 00:04:13.815
If all you hear is profile button,

103
00:04:14.155 --> 00:04:15.695
the screen reader has no idea.

104
00:04:15.765 --> 00:04:18.055
This is just one piece of a bigger component.

105
00:04:18.795 --> 00:04:21.335
But dynamic content isn't just about things you click

106
00:04:21.335 --> 00:04:22.415
on like tabs.

107
00:04:22.845 --> 00:04:24.855
It's also about things that update on their own,

108
00:04:25.155 --> 00:04:27.255
and that is where live regions come in.

109
00:04:27.685 --> 00:04:28.935
This is basically the magic

110
00:04:28.935 --> 00:04:31.255
that lets a screen reader announce changes happening

111
00:04:31.255 --> 00:04:34.295
somewhere else on the page, like a confirmation message

112
00:04:34.355 --> 00:04:36.575
or updated search results without the user

113
00:04:36.575 --> 00:04:37.655
having to go hunt for them.

114
00:04:38.525 --> 00:04:41.465
And this is a perfect example of a key design decision.

115
00:04:41.885 --> 00:04:43.385
Should an announcement be polite

116
00:04:43.485 --> 00:04:45.585
and maybe wait for the user to pause what they're doing?

117
00:04:46.045 --> 00:04:48.585
Or should it be assertive interrupting immediately

118
00:04:48.585 --> 00:04:49.905
because the info is critical?

119
00:04:50.335 --> 00:04:52.665
Item added to cart can probably be polite,

120
00:04:53.005 --> 00:04:55.025
but a warning that your session is about to expire.

121
00:04:55.055 --> 00:04:56.305
Yeah, that needs to be assertive

122
00:04:56.605 --> 00:04:59.105
and you the designer get to decide that priority.

123
00:04:59.955 --> 00:05:02.205
Whew. Okay, we have covered a lot

124
00:05:02.205 --> 00:05:03.965
of pretty complex ground here.

125
00:05:04.225 --> 00:05:06.525
So how do we tie this all together into something you can

126
00:05:06.725 --> 00:05:09.525
actually remember and you, let's boil it all down

127
00:05:09.525 --> 00:05:11.205
to a simple, powerful framework

128
00:05:11.205 --> 00:05:13.005
for testing any component you design.

129
00:05:13.715 --> 00:05:16.685
It's just three questions. First, did I hear context?

130
00:05:17.115 --> 00:05:19.285
That goes back to our data tables with their headers

131
00:05:19.345 --> 00:05:20.885
and our forms with their group labels.

132
00:05:21.265 --> 00:05:22.925
Second, does focus go where?

133
00:05:22.965 --> 00:05:24.725
I expect that's our modal dialogue.

134
00:05:24.725 --> 00:05:27.005
Test focus moves in, stays trapped,

135
00:05:27.065 --> 00:05:28.405
and then returns properly.

136
00:05:28.945 --> 00:05:31.165
And third, am I told when something changes

137
00:05:31.475 --> 00:05:32.925
that covers our tab selections.

138
00:05:32.925 --> 00:05:34.885
In all those dynamic live region updates.

139
00:05:35.625 --> 00:05:37.445
And here's the most important point of all.

140
00:05:37.635 --> 00:05:41.125
Your job isn't to know all the specific area attributes

141
00:05:41.125 --> 00:05:42.205
or JavaScript functions.

142
00:05:42.515 --> 00:05:44.165
Your job is to know what a good,

143
00:05:44.175 --> 00:05:46.005
solid user experience sounds like.

144
00:05:46.665 --> 00:05:48.245
You really don't need to know the code.

145
00:05:48.505 --> 00:05:50.245
You just need to know what to listen for.

146
00:05:51.005 --> 00:05:53.925
Recognizing these auditory patterns, that's your superpower.

147
00:05:54.835 --> 00:05:56.255
So I'm gonna leave you with this.

148
00:05:56.755 --> 00:05:58.365
The next time you're testing your work,

149
00:05:58.735 --> 00:06:00.965
don't just look at it, put on some headphones

150
00:06:01.105 --> 00:06:02.405
and actually listen to it

151
00:06:02.625 --> 00:06:04.285
and ask yourself those three questions.

152
00:06:04.825 --> 00:06:06.085
Am I hearing the right context?

153
00:06:06.745 --> 00:06:08.325
Am I in control of where I am

154
00:06:08.665 --> 00:06:10.245
and am I being told about change?

155
00:06:10.785 --> 00:06:12.405
If you can answer yes to all three of those,

156
00:06:12.785 --> 00:06:14.925
you are well on your way to building something

157
00:06:14.995 --> 00:06:16.685
that truly works for everyone.
